To determine the effect of B[ALPHA]P on the gene signature in human T lymphocytes, primary cultures of T lymphocytes purified from healthy blood donors and activated with anti-CD3 and anti-CD28 antibodies for 72 h, were used and co-exposed to 2 M B[ALPHA]P for the last 48 h. We previously reported an early and functional up-regulation of the Aryl Hydrocarbon by such human T lymphocyte activation during 24 h, followed by a maximal response of target genes such as CYP1A1 and CYP1B1 after exposure to 2 M B[ALPHA]P. Such a 2 M concentration is in the range of B[ALPHA]P concentrations known to lead to maximal response of target genes in cultured human cells.
